check-lxdialog.sh: give its probe program an explicit `int main(void)`.

Busybox 1.36.1's scripts/kconfig/lxdialog/check-lxdialog.sh ships the
classic K&R probe:

    #include CURSES_LOC
    main() {}

This is also what Linux's kconfig carried for years and it compiles
fine on GCC up through 13-ish: the implicit-int return type is a
warning, not an error. Clang 16+ (including Apple clang) promotes
`-Wimplicit-int` to an error by default, so on macOS hosts the probe
now fails with

    error: type specifier missing, defaults to 'int' [-Wimplicit-int]

...even when ncurses itself is perfectly discoverable via pkg-config.
The Makefile then rejects the menuconfig build with the misleading
"Unable to find the ncurses libraries" banner, which sends the user
chasing a ghost (libncursesw is installed, headers are visible, the
real .o files link fine with the same flags — only the probe is broken).

Give the probe an explicit prototype so it compiles cleanly under
both GCC and modern clang. Strictly additive (adds `int` / `void` /
`return 0;`) and does not alter what the probe actually tests.

--- a/scripts/kconfig/lxdialog/check-lxdialog.sh
+++ b/scripts/kconfig/lxdialog/check-lxdialog.sh
@@ -47,7 +47,7 @@
 check() {
         $cc -x c - -o $tmp 2>/dev/null <<'EOF'
 #include CURSES_LOC
-main() {}
+int main(void) { return 0; }
 EOF
 	if [ $? != 0 ]; then
 	    echo " *** Unable to find the ncurses libraries or the"       1>&2
